1ï¸âƒ£ The Design of Everyday Things â€” Don Norman
Core Idea: Good design makes things understandable; bad design makes people feel stupid.
Key Concepts:
Affordances: The design should hint what it can do (e.g., a button looks tappable).
Feedback: Every user action should have an immediate, visible response.
Constraints: Guide users by limiting wrong actions.
For MSME UX:
â†’ Every page must feel self-explanatory. If the user wonders â€œwhat next?â€, the design failed.
â†’ Example: A â€œDispatch Orderâ€ button should be big, primary-colored, and give instant success feedback (â€œDispatched âœ…â€).

2ï¸âƒ£ Donâ€™t Make Me Think â€” Steve Krug
Core Idea: Usability = clarity. Users shouldnâ€™t have to think to navigate.
Key Concepts:
Self-evident navigation â†’ labels that describe exactly what happens next.
Minimize cognitive load â†’ donâ€™t make users remember where they came from.
Test early, test cheap â†’ even 3â€“5 users can reveal 80% of issues.
For MSME UX:
â†’ Replace complex terms like â€œProduction Reconciliationâ€ with â€œCheck Finished Goodsâ€.
â†’ Keep core workflows 1â€“2 taps deep (e.g., Order â†’ Produce â†’ Dispatch).

3ï¸âƒ£ Lean UX â€” Jeff Gothelf & Josh Seiden
